##Many Chinese have started to buy face masks on Wechat

Weixin Signal Wowjiemian

Function introduction, the interface news is China has the influence original financial and economic new media, only serves the independent thinking crowd

By Liu Yujing

Editor | Ya Han-hsiang

“

Because of the shortage of masks, wechat and wechat groups selling masks became popular among Chinese in the United States, and various wechat groups became channels for people to exchange their needs.

”

“

Because of the shortage of masks, wechat and wechat groups selling masks became popular among Chinese in the United States, and various wechat groups became channels for people to exchange their needs.

”

The new-crown pneumonia epidemic in the United States is beginning to spread across the board, and health supplies are becoming unmarketable in the United States. Earlier, someone posted on social media that there were plenty of masks in the US, and wal-mart sold 20 pieces for $2.97. But that may not be the case.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Pictures circulating on the Internet show that there are plenty of masks in wal-mart stores in the United States.

Dr. Zhang Liang, who is reading in Atlanta, told interface news that Walmart's low-cost mask, which he had seen on his website for sale two months earlier, was out of stock every time he looked it up, it's out of stock, too.

"I've seen the price map of this mask several times, but I don't dare go to Walmart to see if it's available, " Los Angeles resident Lin Shaodan told interface news, "The masks I know cost a lot more than that, and Amazon is full of third-party sellers, with 3m 8511 masks sometimes selling for $24.95 each. "

Several Chinese who live in California, New York and elsewhere told interface news that masks were out of stock at nearby retailers including Wal Mart, Target, Home Depo and CVS, the last time they were bought was in January. Products such as toilet paper, Sanitary Napkins and hand sanitizer are often snapped up on the shelves.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A Target supermarket in Orange County, Los Angeles, recently stocked with hygiene products. Photo: Li Xiaolan

So far, a group of Chinese living in the United States bought masks in late January and early February, before the outbreak spread widely in the United States, and there were $9.100 masks on Amazon, amazon's official Amazon Prime also shows that masks are in stock.

Since then, with the epidemic gradually severe, offline retailers and online e-commerce are facing a shortage of masks, which has also spawned a number of overpriced third-party sellers. According to CNBC, a third-party seller on Amazon at one point raised the price of the mask by 582% due to a lack of official channels. Amazon said last week that, they removed more than a million consumer and personal protection products from the platform that violated pricing rules and false advertising.

In addition to the shortage of face masks in some U.S. hospitals, a children's Hospital in Seattle has put up signs outside its doors to accept donations of face masks. On Twitter, a number of nonprofit groups have compiled lists of items that are currently in short supply, including Masks, masks, protective clothing, disposable gloves, alcohol cotton ball and so on.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A sign outside a children's Hospital in Seattle.

For now, though, third-party mask sellers on Amazon and Ebay are spotty, even as the platform has begun to shake things up.

Some chinese-americans told interface news that most of the third-party sales were made in China for export, but the quality and brand had to be carefully identified, with most of the 50 masks selling for between $20 and $30.

Zhang Liang bought 50 disposable surgical masks on Ebay two weeks ago for $28. "They're already cheap in the U.S. , " he told interface news. Wu, who lives in San Francisco Bay Area, found a Chinese seller on Amazon and bought 50 masks shipped from China for $29.

WECHAT and wechat groups selling face masks have become popular among Chinese in the United States. Wechat groups of various colors have become channels for people to exchange their needs. People are beginning to sell face masks in their friend circles.

Like third-party sellers on Amazon, "some wechat masks are too cheap to be trusted, but they're too expensive to be trusted, " said Lin, who sells $3.50 masks on the Chinese wechat group in Los Angeles, domestic manufacturers of regular medical masks, logistics generation.

Lin's girlfriend bought $38.50 masks from another relatively reliable wechat merchant, also shipped to the United States by a Chinese manufacturer.

Face masks are more in demand and better informed among the Chinese community, not least because most of the people who wear and buy them are Chinese.

"Eighty percent of people in Asian supermarkets wear masks, but when you go to Costco and other mass markets, you have to wear them yourself. I went to the DMV to do business before and was discriminated against for wearing masks, " Shen told interface news, she works as an art curator at an art gallery in Los Angeles, but hasn't been out in three days because of the outbreak. The last time she bought a mask was in mid-january, and none of the masks she bought from third-party vendors across the platforms have been shipped since.
